<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">
  Comparison of positive and negative behaviour entries by residential location – last 28 days
</h3>
<p>
  This visual shows the total count and proportions of casenote entries related to behaviour over the last 28-day period.
  This means casenotes entered into NOMIS as positive or negative entries.
</p>
<p>
  This chart is intended to be a reflection of wing-level activity in the 28-day period.
  So the visuals are a count of all casenotes given to a prisoner when they were on a specific wing, even if the prisoner has since been moved.
  As a result, a prisoner can have casenotes on multiple wings in the 28-day period.
</p>
<p>
  <a href="/analytics/behaviour-entries#heading-entries-by-location">
    View comparison of positive and negative behaviour entries by residential location – last 28 days chart
  </a>
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">
  Percentage and number of prisoners receiving each behaviour entry type by residential location – last 28 days
</h3>
<p>
  This visual shows how many prisoners, who have stayed on a given wing over a 28-day period, have received:
</p>
<ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
  <li>
    1 or more only positive casenote – Positive
  </li>
  <li>
    1 or more only negative casenote – Negative
  </li>
  <li>
    1 or more positive and 1 or more negative casenote – Both
  </li>
  <li>
    No casenotes (positive or negative) – None
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  As all prisoners fit into one of these 4 categories.
  If a prisoner has moved wing within the 28-day period they will be counted in each wing they have stayed (regardless of how long they spent there).
  Therefore the total number of prisoners in this visual will be equal to or - most likely - larger than the number of prisoners that are in any prison or wing at any one time.
</p>
<p>
  New entrants into a wing will automatically be allocated to the None type until they receive a casenote.
  If there is a large number of movements between wings in a short space of time within the 28-day period it is likely to be shown in the None column.
</p>
<p>
  The colours of the boxes in the visual correspond to the percentage, not the count, of prisoners in the wing that are in each category (or the entire prison in the first row).
</p>
<p>
