</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m" id="calculating-all-row-for-entries">
  Calculations of ‘All’ in behaviour entry charts – establishment, group and national
</h3>
<p>
  If a prisoner has moved wing within the 28-day period, any behaviour entries are counted in each wing they have stayed (regardless of how long they spent there).
  So the number of  All entries in all but the first row will be equal to or - most likely - larger than the number of prisoners in this location at any one time.
</p>
<p>
  But the number of prisoners in the first ‘All’ row might be slightly less than the total tally of all subsequent location rows, because this data only looks at the types of case notes a prisoner has received whilst in the prison for the 28-day period regardless of the wing they have been on.
</p>
<p>
  For example:
  <br />
  There are 3 wings (A, B and C)
</p>
<ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
  <li>
    Prisoner A moved across all 3 wings in the last 28 days
  </li>
  <li>
    They receive a positive casenote in wing A, a negative in wing B, and none in wing C
  </li>
  <li>
    If we were to sum up, they would count as 1 Positive, 1 Negative and 1 None in the All columns of the relevant
    wings
  </li>
  <li>
    The All column calculation looks solely at the prison level where this prisoner counts as 1 for Both as they received a positive and a negative casenote in the prison within the 28-day period
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">
  Comparison of positive and negative behaviour entries in the establishment – last 12 months
</h3>
<p>
  This visual shows the monthly count of positive and negative casenotes over a 12 month period in the chosen prison.
</p>
<p>
  The average monthly prison population is shown in the table for additional context when looking at the total number of prisoners.
  This is calculated by adding the number of prisoners for each day of the month in MoJAP NOMIS, and then dividing them by the number of successful NOMIS snapshots into MoJAP NOMIS.
</p>
<p>
  This is important to take into consideration when looking at the chart, as it is looking at the total number of casenotes issued.
  For example, a drop in overall casenotes issued could be explained by a shrinking prison population as opposed to any behavioural or policy change.
</p>
<p>
  This visual only considers complete months, so the current month does not appear.
</p>
